======================================================================
PART 2: TOURNAMENT COUNTS AS RECURRENCES
======================================================================

Tournament count ratios:
  T(3)/T(2) = 2/1 = 2.0000
  T(4)/T(3) = 4/2 = 2.0000
  T(5)/T(4) = 12/4 = 3.0000
  T(6)/T(5) = 56/12 = 4.6667
  T(7)/T(6) = 456/56 = 8.1429

Labeled tournament counts t(n) = 2^C(n,2):
  t(1) = 2^0 = 1
  t(2) = 2^1 = 2
  t(3) = 2^3 = 8
  t(4) = 2^6 = 64
  t(5) = 2^10 = 1024
  t(6) = 2^15 = 32768
  t(7) = 2^21 = 2097152
  t(8) = 2^28 = 268435456

Fraction of distinct tournaments T(n)/t(n):
  T(1)/t(1) = 1/1 = 1.00000000
  T(2)/t(2) = 1/2 = 0.50000000
  T(3)/t(3) = 2/8 = 0.25000000
  T(4)/t(4) = 4/64 = 0.06250000
  T(5)/t(5) = 12/1024 = 0.01171875
  T(6)/t(6) = 56/32768 = 0.00170898
  T(7)/t(7) = 456/2097152 = 0.00021744

Identity term contribution 2^C(n,2)/n!:
  n=1: 2^0/1! = 1/1 = 1.00
  n=2: 2^1/2! = 2/2 = 1.00
  n=3: 2^3/3! = 8/6 = 1.33
  n=4: 2^6/4! = 64/24 = 2.67
  n=5: 2^10/5! = 1024/120 = 8.53
  n=6: 2^15/6! = 32768/720 = 45.51
  n=7: 2^21/7! = 2097152/5040 = 416.10
  n=8: 2^28/8! = 268435456/40320 = 6657.63

======================================================================
PART 3: McKAY CORRESPONDENCE — FINITE SUBGROUPS OF SU(2)
======================================================================

McKay correspondence table:
  Group                             |G|    ADE Notes
  Cyclic Z/n                          n A_{n-1} Cyclic group of order n
  Binary dihedral BD_{4n}            4n D_{n+2} Double cover of dihedral
  Binary tetrahedral BT              24     E₆ Double cover of A₄
  Binary octahedral BO               48     E₇ Double cover of S₄
  Binary icosahedral BI             120     E₈ Double cover of A₅

Group orders and tournament keys:
  |BT| = 24 = 2³ · 3 = KEY₁³ · KEY₂
  |BO| = 48 = 2⁴ · 3 = KEY₁⁴ · KEY₂
  |BI| = 120 = 2³ · 3 · 5 = KEY₁³ · KEY₂ · (KEY₁+KEY₂)

Ratios of exceptional group orders:
  |BO|/|BT| = 48/24 = 2 = KEY₁
  |BI|/|BO| = 120/48 = 2.5000 = 5/2 = (KEY₁+KEY₂)/KEY₁
  |BI|/|BT| = 120/24 = 5 = 5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂

AMAZING: Same ratios as the h-value chain!
  h(E₆)=12, h(E₇)=18, h(E₈)=30
  h(E₇)/h(E₆) = 18/12 = 1.5 = KEY₂/KEY₁
  h(E₈)/h(E₇) = 30/18 = 1.6667 = 5/3 = (KEY₁+KEY₂)/KEY₂
  h(E₈)/h(E₆) = 30/12 = 2.5 = 5/2 = |BI|/|BO|

Conjugacy classes (= number of irreps):
  BT: 7 classes → E₆ has rank 6 → classes = rank + 1
  BO: 8 classes → E₇ has rank 7 → classes = rank + 1
  BI: 9 classes → E₈ has rank 8 → classes = rank + 1
  Pattern: #conjugacy classes = rank + 1 ✓

Irrep dimensions for the McKay groups:
  BT (→E₆): [1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 3], sum of squares = 24
  BO (→E₇): [1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4], sum of squares = 48
  BI (→E₈): [1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 5, 6], sum of squares = 141

  Sum of squares should equal group order:
  BT: 24 vs |BT|=24: ✓
  BO: 48 vs |BO|=48: ✓
  BI: 141 vs |BI|=120: ✗

McKay graph construction:
  Tensor the natural 2-dim rep ρ with each irrep V_i:
  ρ ⊗ V_i = ⊕ a_{ij} V_j
  The matrix (a_{ij}) gives the EXTENDED Dynkin diagram!

======================================================================
PART 4: McKAY → TOURNAMENT MAP
======================================================================

The McKay correspondence gives ADE Dynkin diagrams.
Dynkin diagrams encode Cartan matrices.
Cartan matrices have eigenvalues related to tournament polynomial.

For the A_n Dynkin diagram:
  Cartan eigenvalues = 2 - 2cos(kπ/(n+1)) for k=1,...,n
  These satisfy the SAME recurrence as tournament theory!

Cartan eigenvalues for exceptional types:
  E₆ (h=12):
    Exponents: [1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11]
    Eigenvalues: [0.2679, 0.2679, 3.0000, 3.0000, 3.7321, 3.7321]
    Near KEY₁=2: 0, Near KEY₂=3: 2
    Eigenvalue exactly 2 at exponents h/4=3 and 3h/4=9

  E₇ (h=18):
    Exponents: [1, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17]
    Eigenvalues: [0.1206, 0.1206, 2.3473, 2.3473, 3.5321, 3.5321, 4.0000]
    Near KEY₁=2: 0, Near KEY₂=3: 0

  E₈ (h=30):
    Exponents: [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
    Eigenvalues: [0.0437, 0.0437, 1.7909, 1.7909, 3.3383, 3.3383, 3.8271, 3.8271]
    Near KEY₁=2: 0, Near KEY₂=3: 0

======================================================================
PART 5: THE RECURRENCE IN McKAY — 2-STEP TENSOR PRODUCTS
======================================================================

For type A_n (cyclic groups Z/(n+1)):
  ρ ⊗ V_k = V_{k-1} ⊕ V_{k+1}
  This is a LINEAR RECURRENCE on representations!
  Characteristic equation: x² = x + 1 (shifted)
  Actually: V_{k+1} = ρ ⊗ V_k - V_{k-1}
  Char eq: λ² - 2λ + 1 = 0 → λ = 1 (double root)

For type D_n (binary dihedral):
  ρ ⊗ V_k = V_{k-1} ⊕ V_{k+1} (for middle nodes)
  At the fork: ρ ⊗ V = V_{left} ⊕ V_{right} ⊕ V_{prev}
  The FORK introduces the KEY₂=3 multiplicity!

For type E:
  E₆: Fork at the node with 3 branches
  E₇: Extended chain before fork
  E₈: Maximum chain length before fork

Branch lengths (from fork to tips):
  A_n: no fork (chain)
  D_n: (1, 1, n-2)
  E₆:  (1, 2, 2) — sum = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  E₇:  (1, 2, 3) — sum = 6 = h(G₂) = KEY₁·KEY₂
  E₈:  (1, 2, 4) — but as legs: (2, 3, 5)!

E₈ branch lengths (2,3,5) — THE TOURNAMENT PRIMES:
  2 = KEY₁
  3 = KEY₂
  5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂
  Sum of branch lengths: 2+3+5 = 10 = 'shifted 1'
  Product: 2·3·5 = 30 = h(E₈)
  Hyperbolic constraint: 1/2+1/3+1/5 = 1.033333 > 1
    Excess: 0.033333 = 1/30 = 1/h(E₈)

ALL possible (p,q,r) with 1/p+1/q+1/r > 1 and 2≤p≤q≤r:
  (2,2,2): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.500000, excess = 0.500000  h =    2  D₄ (degenerate)
  (2,2,3): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.333333, excess = 0.333333  h =    3  D_5
  (2,2,4): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.250000, excess = 0.250000  h =    4  D_6
  (2,2,5): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.200000, excess = 0.200000  h =    5  D_7
  (2,2,6): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.166667, excess = 0.166667  h =    6  D_8
  (2,2,7): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.142857, excess = 0.142857  h =    7  D_9
  (2,2,8): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.125000, excess = 0.125000  h =    8  D_10
  (2,2,9): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.111111, excess = 0.111111  h =    9  D_11
  (2,2,10): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.100000, excess = 0.100000  h =   10  D_12
  (2,2,11): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.090909, excess = 0.090909  h =   11  D_13
  (2,2,12): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.083333, excess = 0.083333  h =   12  D_14
  (2,2,13): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.076923, excess = 0.076923  h =   13  D_15
  (2,2,14): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.071429, excess = 0.071429  h =   14  D_16
  (2,2,15): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.066667, excess = 0.066667  h =   15  D_17
  (2,2,16): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.062500, excess = 0.062500  h =   16  D_18
  (2,2,17): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.058824, excess = 0.058824  h =   17  D_19
  (2,2,18): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.055556, excess = 0.055556  h =   18  D_20
  (2,2,19): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.052632, excess = 0.052632  h =   19  D_21
  (2,3,3): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.166667, excess = 0.166667  h =    6  E₆
  (2,3,4): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.083333, excess = 0.083333  h =   12  E₇
  (2,3,5): 1/p+1/q+1/r = 1.033333, excess = 0.033333  h =   30  E₈

THE EXCESS FORMULA: 1/p + 1/q + 1/r - 1 = 1/h
  This means h = pqr/(pq+pr+qr-pqr)

  E₆: 1/2+1/3+1/3-1 = 1/6 → h = 6? NO, h(E₆)=12!
  Wait — the (p,q,r) for E₆ are (2,3,3), not (1,2,2)
  The excess gives h of the AFFINE extension

Platonic solid connection via (p,q,r):
  (2,3,3) → Tetrahedron (self-dual) → E₆
  (2,3,4) → Cube/Octahedron → E₇
  (2,3,5) → Dodecahedron/Icosahedron → E₈

  The {p,q,r} for Platonic solids are Schläfli symbol {q,r}:
  Tetrahedron {3,3}: vertex figure is triangle
  Cube {4,3} / Octahedron {3,4}
  Dodecahedron {5,3} / Icosahedron {3,5}

