PART 6: T(6) = 56 — DEEPER STRUCTURE
======================================================================

56 = T(6) = dim(minuscule E₇)

The E₇ minuscule representation V(ω₇):
  - 56-dimensional
  - Weights form the 56 vertices of a polytope
  - The weight lattice of E₇ has det = 2 = KEY₁

56 = C(8,3) = C(rank(E₈), KEY₂)

Possible explanations for the coincidence:
  1. Pure numerology: 56 just happens to be both T(6) and dim(V_E₇)
  2. C(8,3): choosing 3-element subsets of an 8-set
     E₇ ⊂ E₈ (rank 7 inside rank 8)
     The 56-rep of E₇ = restriction of some E₈ structure
     Choosing KEY₂=3 roots from rank(E₈)=8 positions?

Computing T(6) via Burnside:
  T(6) = (1/6!) Σ_{σ∈S₆} 2^{c(σ)}
  where c(σ) = number of orbits of σ on the 15 edges

       Cycle type   #perms  c(σ)        2^c    Contribution
              [6]      120     3          8             960
           [5, 1]      144     3          8            1152
           [4, 2]       90     5         32            2880
        [4, 1, 1]       90     5         32            2880
           [3, 3]       40     5         32            1280
        [3, 2, 1]      120     5         32            3840
     [3, 1, 1, 1]       40     7        128            5120
        [2, 2, 2]       15     9        512            7680
     [2, 2, 1, 1]       45     9        512           23040
  [2, 1, 1, 1, 1]       15    11       2048           30720
  [1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1]        1    15      32768           32768

  Total = 112320
  T(6) = 112320/720 = 156

Verification — T(n) for n=1..7:
  T(1) = 1
  T(2) = 2
  T(3) = 4
  T(4) = 11
  T(5) = 34
  T(6) = 156
  T(7) = 1044

