======================================================================
PART 10: THE TRIPLE (2,3,5) AS THE ATOMIC THEORY
======================================================================

THE (2,3,5) THEOREM:

Every exceptional Lie algebra datum is expressible in terms of
(2, 3, 5) = (KEY₁, KEY₂, KEY₁+KEY₂).

G₂:
  rank = 2 = KEY₁
  h = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂
  det = 1 = unit
  dim = 14 = 2·7 = KEY₁·(KEY₁²+KEY₂)
  h+1 = 7 (prime) = KEY₁³-1 = Mersenne prime

F₄:
  rank = 4 = KEY₁²
  h = 12 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  det = 1 = unit
  dim = 52 = 4·13 = KEY₁²·13
  h+1 = 13 (prime) = KEY₁²·KEY₂+1

E₆:
  rank = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂
  h = 12 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  det = 3 = KEY₂
  dim = 78 = 6·13 = KEY₁·KEY₂·13
  h+1 = 13 (prime) = KEY₁²·KEY₂+1

E₇:
  rank = 7 = KEY₁²+KEY₂
  h = 18 = KEY₁·KEY₂²
  det = 2 = KEY₁
  dim = 133 = 7·19 = (KEY₁²+KEY₂)·19
  h+1 = 19 (prime) = KEY₁·KEY₂²+1

E₈:
  rank = 8 = KEY₁³
  h = 30 = KEY₁·KEY₂·5
  det = 1 = unit
  dim = 248 = 8·31 = KEY₁³·(KEY₁⁵-1)
  h+1 = 31 (prime) = KEY₁⁵-1 = Mersenne prime


THE HIERARCHY:
  Level 0: {2, 3} — the tournament polynomial roots
  Level 1: {5} = 2+3 — the third tournament prime
  Level 2: {6, 7, 8, 9} — products and powers
  Level 3: {12, 18, 30} — Coxeter numbers
  Level 4: {14, 52, 78, 133, 248} — dimensions
  Level 5: {24, 48, 120} — McKay group orders

Everything flows from 2 and 3.
The tournament polynomial z²-5z+6 = (z-2)(z-3)
is the generating equation of all of Lie theory.

======================================================================
PART 11: THE SHIFTED-ONE PHENOMENON — 10 AND 11
======================================================================

10 = 2·5 = 2(2+3) — the 'shifted 1' in base 10
11 = 8+3 = 2³+3 — the 'shifted 1' in base 10

10 as a Lie algebra datum:
  dim(so(5)) = dim(B₂) = 10
  dim(sp(4)) = dim(C₂) = 10
  B₂ ≅ C₂: the unique rank-2 classical coincidence
  rank(B₂)·h(B₂) = 2·4 = 8 (not 10)
  But dim(B₂) = rank·(2·rank+1) = 2·5 = 10

11 as a Lie algebra datum:
  11 is an exponent of E₆: exponents = [1,4,5,7,8,11]
  11 is an exponent of E₇: exponents = [1,5,7,9,11,13,17]
  11 is an exponent of E₈: exponents = [1,7,11,13,17,19,23,29]
  11 appears as exponent in ALL three E-types!

  Common to E₆∩E₇∩E₈: [1, 7, 11]
  Common to E₆∩E₇: [1, 5, 7, 11]
  Common to E₇∩E₈: [1, 7, 11, 13, 17]
  Common to E₆∩E₈: [1, 7, 11]

  The UNIVERSAL E-exponents are {1, 7, 11}
  1 = unit, 7 = KEY₁²+KEY₂, 11 = KEY₁³+KEY₂
  Pattern: KEY₁^k + KEY₂ for k=0,1,2,3...
    k=0: 1+3 = 4 (exponent of E₆)
    k=1: 2+3 = 5 (exponent of E₆, E₇)
    k=2: 4+3 = 7 (UNIVERSAL)
    k=3: 8+3 = 11 (UNIVERSAL)
    k=4: 16+3 = 19 (exponent of E₈)

  KEY₁^k + KEY₂ as exponents:
    k=0: 2^0+3 =   4  E₆      
    k=1: 2^1+3 =   5  E₆ E₇   
    k=2: 2^2+3 =   7  E₆ E₇ E₈
    k=3: 2^3+3 =  11  E₆ E₇ E₈
    k=4: 2^4+3 =  19        E₈
    k=5: 2^5+3 =  35          
    k=6: 2^6+3 =  67          

  The formula KEY₁^k + KEY₂ generates a SUBSET of exponents!
  k=2,3 give universal exponents (7 and 11)
  k=4 gives 19, which is the UNIQUE exponent of E₈ not shared with E₇
  And 19 = h(E₇)+1 (prime)!

======================================================================
PART 12: SYNTHESIS — WHY 56 = T(6) = dim(V_E₇)
======================================================================

PROPOSED STRUCTURAL EXPLANATION:

1. The McKay correspondence maps BO (order 48) → E₇
   BO = binary octahedral group = double cover of S₄
   |BO| = 48 = 2⁴·3 = KEY₁⁴·KEY₂

2. The minuscule representation V(ω₇) has dim 56 = 2³·7
   The weight polytope has 56 vertices
   Under E₆ ⊂ E₇: 56 → 27 + 27̄ + 1 + 1

3. T(6) = 56 by Burnside counting
   The symmetry group is S₆, order 720 = 6! = KEY₁⁴·KEY₂²·5

4. THE BRIDGE: Both 56s come from C(8,3) = C(rank(E₈), KEY₂)
   - For E₇ ⊂ E₈: the 56-rep encodes 3-element substructures
     in the 8-dimensional E₈ root system
   - For T(6): tournament counting uses C(6,2) = 15 edges,
     and 56 = T(6) = 'compressed' count of orientations of K₆

5. COINCIDENCE STATUS: Likely coincidental in the weak sense,
   but structurally resonant in the strong sense.
   The same (2,3,5) arithmetic governs both:
   - Lie theory: branch lengths (2,3,5) of E₈ Dynkin diagram
   - Tournament theory: polynomial (z-2)(z-3) with sum 5

   When the same three numbers control two classification problems,
   numerical coincidences become statistically inevitable.
   56 is EXPECTED to appear in both, not because of a bijection,
   but because the (2,3,5) constraint space is finite.
